headline: Labor Day Facebook Free for All on 'The Five'

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Happy Labor Day, everyone. I'm Juan Williams. Along with Kimberly Guilfoyle, Jesse Watters, Dana Perino, and yes, it's Greg Gutfeld. It's 9 o'clock in New York City and this is "The Five." It's Labor Day, the unofficial end to summer. It has been quite a busy one for us in the news business. Usually, summers are a slow season. But this one was anything but. So, as the summer winds down, we thought we would have some fun tonight and turn the show over to you, again this holiday, with another Facebook Free for All. We'll answer questions you have for us throughout the hour. You posted them on our page: facebook.com/thefivefnc.  So, where to begin? It is a simple thing, it's a question from Steve C. What was the highlight of your summer? We'll go to Miss Summery Dana Perino.

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: It's been a great summer. People say that I have a place to go on the weekends, Peter and I have a place in South Carolina. But we change. In this year, we have a place in Jersey Shore. So, I became kind of a jersey girl this year. But it's been really great because it's good for Peter and for Jasper, of course, he loves to fish and go on the beach. So, the highlight of my summer has been being able to make a lot of new friends and get out in the fresh air on the weekends.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: So, the highlight is getting a second vacation home?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: No, that's not really what I said.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, it is Labor Day. And one works hard.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I saw that you were crossing yourselves.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh, this reminds me of the -- well, the Hamptons was great this summer.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I didn't make it to the Hamptons this summer.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, my goodness. Jesse, what was it like for you?

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: I say that my tan was the highlight. I've done it hard this year. I learned a lot about it. You know, you got to start with 30 on the face, then you go to 15, and then you go down to eight. And then at the end of the summer, you can use self-tanner.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: No, this is not true.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That is true.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: That is fake sunscreen news.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That is not fake news. Look of his tanned skin. This is the result --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, my gosh.   Well, what was the truth?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: No, you should always wear SPF 45 on your face.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: She's pale. Okay. That is makeup.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, let's go to the beautiful one.

utterances.speaker: KIMBERLY GUILFOYLE, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Well --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Excuse me, Juan.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He just basically dissed all of us.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, no, go right ahead. Go right ahead.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: So, my summer, the highlight was definitely going with my son and visiting his camp and doing, you know, fun summer stuff with him. So, I always loved to play with him and having hot tub parties with him. That is our favorite thing to do, with salami snacks.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, good food. But when he go to camp with a guy, how old is he?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Oh, he's ten. He's going to be 11. You go to camp to visit for the day and you get --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, you're the mom.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But you don't have to like, jump over logs and stuff?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: No, no, but I love to. I love to jump it on the soccer game.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: On a soccer game.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I only get the ball when it's kicked out-of-bounds.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So, I think the most interesting person on THE FIVE is Greg. So, Greg, you must have had the most interesting summer. Right?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Actually. The high point of my summer was -- I totally forgot that I had HBO. So, I spent an entire Sunday watching "Westworld." It was like 11 episodes in a row. I didn't leave my apartment, it was like -- it started Saturday evening to Sunday afternoon. I laughed, I cried, I was horrified, I was shocked. It was like the best summer event of my life.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Are you getting paid by "Westworld"? Is that a plug?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No, it was just like, I like watching TV.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I always get called a "Westworld" robot.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It is a compliment. It means you are perfect.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Excuse me. Excuse me. I am so confused. It was summer, Greg. You are supposed to go outside and get fresh air. Remember what Dana said --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: My brain got fresh air by watching "Westworld." My brain frolicked in the imagination of Michael Crichton's universe.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That is how you don't get tan, everybody.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Wow. I'm disappointed. I thought you were going to go to some wild music festival and --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I went to a wedding. I went to a wedding.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: He's a Greek. I mean --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You went to Greece and then like stayed inside and watched HBO.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Greece was overrated. Look, Greece was a pain in the neck. I mean, you got -- it's a lot of traveling for a wedding. I didn't even know the people. But I did it as a favor to my wife. They are not watching. They are in Greece.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Okay.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I think.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: They don't get FOX News in Greece?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No, maybe they're not in Greece. I don't know. All I know is, you know, destination weddings are very selfish.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: No, they are not.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes, they are.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: They give people a chance to have fun and go on vacation that they otherwise might not take.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: A destination wedding is designed for two reasons.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: One, to show off, and two, to eliminate people you don't want to come.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes. To weed out like the poor people, or the people, the fringe friends.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Exactly.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Destination weddings are selfish, greedy, and strange.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: No, they're not.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And sometimes the fringe friends that are poor actually show up and you're like, what are you doing here?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Except when they are lifesaving to celebrate your nuptials.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I got married at City Hall. Didn't you?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That's the way to do it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: City Hall. The office of birth, death, and marriages.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: With strangers.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And they call it the office of hatches, matches, and dispatches.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Hatches, matches, and dispatches.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: What about you, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes. So, you know, the thing about it, I went to a wedding out in California, Carmel by the sea. I had never been there. And it was terrific, right? And it was actually the 50th anniversary of that famous concert, what's the city right next --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Monterey?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Monterey. Right? So, there are lots of people there. I had never actually been around Monterey and the statue and all the sardine history and all of that. It's pretty cool. Yes. You're exactly right. But I also thought that it was fun, you know, the problem is, I remember once reading a novel and a European woman was complaining that Americans go to too many baseball games in the summer. And it's like boring. Why do you guys go to baseball games? How ordinary, how pedestrian. But actually, my team, the nationals, is having a great season. And I've been having fun going to baseball. If I say that you people, they think, you could have a more interesting life. Anyway --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Well, you should have saved time and watched HBO, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I shouldn't do that. All right?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Okay. So, I apologize that I limp to that. But let's go to this next question.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Jesse, what was your first media job?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: First media job was working here at FOX News.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: What were you doing?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I was working in intake in the basement making $12 an hour.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Tell people what intake is.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: So, you basically label the tapes. Reuters, AP, the President, and then you give them to other people who then put the tapes in the deck and then play them.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Wow!

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: So, basically, I wrote on the tapes, I was making minimum wage, no health insurance, Tuesdays through Sundays, 2:00 p.m. to midnight. Started at the bottom, now I'm on THE FIVE.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: High five.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: What a success story? My first job --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: In media.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Well, I had three jobs. So, I had my own show on court TV.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: That was your first job in media? Holy smokes! I don't think - -

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Anchor of a two-hour show called "both sides."

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Wait a minute. Why would they hire someone with no experience?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Come on, hello.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I say because she's a lawyer.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I mean, it was amazing. So, that was one of my employers. And then I was exclusive prime time to CNN. I was a legal analyst for Larry King on CNN for Anderson Cooper. And then, I was "ABC News" legal analysis. Good Morning America and World News Tonight in the morning.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: If I was your mom, I'd be so proud.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Thank you so much.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Gregory? My first job was president of CNN.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That was it. Yes. Yes. I just walk right into it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, you really screw them up, I will tell you that. They are still recovering.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: My first job, see, this is hard. Because I was an intern for Warner Brothers. When I was in college, so technically, that is media. And I did advertising for motion pictures. So, I was able to promote movies like "Blue Velvet," "The Rivers Edge," Evil Dead 2, that was in 1987 or '86, '87. But then when I graduated, it was that the American spectator as a staff assistant where I made $12,000 a year.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Wow. Was that when the American spectator was really going after the left?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: When haven't they not. It was when they were oversized.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: You are the editor in chief of everything.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. I have climbed that ladder.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: And then, "Red Eye."

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. It climbed up the ladder in a shorter rage.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But men's magazines. So, Dana, is this your first job in media?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: No! I mean, I started -- I worked on a show called "Standoff," which was a public television show in Colorado Springs and I was I guess a producer -- country music DJ at the same time. But "Standoff" was a show that you had a host, and two guest, and they would debate issues. And I helped for the show together, so I guess that would be my first one.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: And also, White House Press Secretary.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I thought --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I started in media and then went to politics and then came back.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Okay. So, my first job in media, you know, it was kind of odd, and I was working my way through college at a paper that's now gone called the Philadelphia evening bulletin. Before that, I was the editor of my Junior High School paper, editor of my High School paper and then I was doing that. But the first job that I really kind of always think of in media was when I was at "The Washington Post," they started doing obituaries.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Oh my God!

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Let me tell you something.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: That's good learning.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Man, it's a terrific thing. Because if you make a mistake, if you misspelled -- like if you put too few Ts and Watters.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Unacceptable.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Unacceptable. Boy, the family will call the publisher.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: By the way, I want to correct my -- I was editor of "The Sarah Friar," Sarah High School. So, that's my first media job.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: There you go.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know who else was the editor? Sarah Friar. Bill Keller. Isn't that amazing?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I never knew that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Isn't that hilarious?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: All right. He was an editor about five or seven years before me.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Sarah is a great school. By the way, you tend to do a lot of kind of obituaries for your one more thing --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: -- that commemorates people --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes. That is because I'm old, Kimberly. So, I actually really want to see who died if I know any of these people.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: No, you're good.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: All right. So, Dana, as your kid, did your family have a Labor Day traditional place that you went?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, my grandfather's ranch was about six and a half hour drive from our house. So, we would usually come back on the Sunday, and I love the school. But in Colorado, you start school a little bit earlier than you do on the East Coast. I think that we probably started the third week of August. So, Labor Day was really just a chance to do homework.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Any traditions, Greg?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. We'd go down by the lake and do things.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, no.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Is it a horror movie?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. Just go down to the lake and we do things. I can't get into it here. But --

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: It's so weird.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But airfare involved?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: We ran out of things to do.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Can we skip the question?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Wait. Wait. What about you, Jesse?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No, no. My dad always wound up in the car driving us somewhere on the Labor Day weekend. So, you know, in the car, my mom playing books on tape. It was horrible. But my sister got car sick so she used to get sick and we'd have to pull over, which I loved to watch, and I enjoyed because I loved watching my sister get sick and I would try to tie my nap, so I would get to watch it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You are such an awful brother.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I'm going to go out of order because Kimberly actually wants to answer the next questions. We are short on time. So, let me just say, in Brooklyn, they have a big Labor Day parade down Eastern Avenue and for me, it was like a thrill to go watch the floats and the people. Now that parade in fact has blown up now at some kind of Caribbean Day parade and its massive crowds and out of control at times. But I love parades. So that was my first favorite parade.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I like that. Yes. But I didn't have a good answer to that so I don't want to let the team down. But I have an excellent answer for number four. Go ahead.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Number four. A Labor Day special for Ms. Guilfoyle, what is your dream retirement destination?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Can anyone guess this at this table and you should be able to?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Ireland.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Mar-A-Lago.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: No. It should be Ireland but what place would I really love.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Virgin Islands.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: No! Villages. Yeheey!

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: We'll wait for you to get there.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I cannot wait to go to the villages.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Really?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: No, I am so serious. People didn't know me really well. No, I love it. I love retirement homes, I love the villages. I just want to go. Any time soon.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, wait a minute. On my book tour, I would like to come, the villages, they buy books.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Oh, no. They are the best.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: All right. Stay right there. Our Labor Day Facebook free-for- all continues next with some of your political questions for THE FIVE. Back in a moment.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Welcome back to our Labor Day Facebook free-for-all. We are having a lot of fun answering your questions and I have some more. This batch is more about patriotism and politics and nature. So, Kimberly, I'll start with you. This is from Ashley R. She wants to know, if you could bring one historical person to the future for the next ten years, who would it be and why?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: So interesting. Isn't it? But I mean, is it too predictable if I say Ronald Reagan?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: No, it's good.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: The first person that came to mind.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I knew you were going to say that.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I have backups, so.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: You don't need a backup.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Okay.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: What about you, Greg?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I would say Calvin Coolidge.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Styling Calvin.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Styling Calvin. And he understood that what it was like to be a leader, which was to, like a child, you know, just be seen and not heard.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I would say, Martin Luther King, Jr. Because I think we could use some of his guidance as a country.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I have a dream.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I am going to go Jesus. Jesus Christ. Because -- and then I get credit to the second coming.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Because you need him.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: That's pretty good.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Nicely done.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You know, so I mean, I was thinking, given that this is a patriotic political segment. I was thinking George Washington is, I don't think people understand, we really wouldn't be America if that guy hadn't said, you know what, I am out, I'm going back to farming. We have a time limited here, presidency, the Democratic process, after the people. So, I would think just to bring him back and say, hey, what he think about what we are doing today, and all the divisions and, you know, the polarization. I think he would --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Also, he could get some real teeth.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes. That would be good.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He would also have to change his name.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh, yes. He owned slaves, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You are ridiculing a real conversation.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Welcome to THE FIVE.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And he set me up.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I had a worse joke. But I didn't use it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: This is from Juliet P. If you could be a member of the opposite political party, of what you currently align, what would you change about your new party?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: So, I'd be a Republican, obviously, no. I would be -- what the opposite of what party I'm in, Dana?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: What are you registered as?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I don't think I'm registered as anything. Really? So, what was the question again?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: So, let's just say that you are a Democrat. What would you want to change about the party?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Change about -- I'd probably work to destroy it from the inside. So, however I could do that, I'd probably go about doing that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right. Juan, if you were not --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, I'm a registered Democrats, so if I was a Republican, I think I would more emphasize the idea that you know what, we need to grow this party. We can't continue playing to a smaller group. We got to play to the bigger crowd. And I'm sure that people would say, we just won everything. I would say, yes, but we got to watch the future.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Okay. That would be an interesting conversation to have it yourself.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes. I have it with my son.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Kimberly, any thoughts?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: That was thoughtful. Yes. So, what I would do is, I would go on the other side and then I would vote for the tax reform and immigration reform and health care in the other direction. Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So, you'd be an elected official.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Is that wrong? Is that bad?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I thought you were just like a member of the party.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: No, no, I would be elected.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I'm not in either -- I'm not the Republican or Democratic Party, so I would have advice for both of them, which is to get rid of the moralism and the basis for the moralism. utterances.utterance: Okay. That would be an interesting conversation to have it yourself.

utterances.utterance: I'm not in either -- I'm not the Republican or Democratic Party, so I would have advice for both of them, which is to get rid of the moralism and the basis for the moralism. utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I was actually, I was going to say about, identity politics as well. utterances.utterance: But, you know, but then Kimberly would like pretty much, you know, scare the crap out of everybody.

utterances.utterance: So, you were sneaking out of this answer?

utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.utterance: I would be a great president because I wouldn't do anything. I would sit at home and watch "Westworld." I would do nothing. I would be Calvin Coolidge.

utterances.utterance: Yes.
